      "content": "Apologies for the confusion. To clarify, the indemnification clause in your contract means that you, as the freelancer, agree to cover the Disclosing Party for any losses, damages, liabilities, or expenses that arise from your actions or inactions related to the agreement. This includes legal fees, settlements, and any other costs associated with claims, lawsuits, or breaches of the agreement.\n\nIn simpler terms, if a third party sues the Disclosing Party because of something you did or didn't do as part of your work, you would be responsible for covering the legal fees and any other related expenses. It's essentially a way for the Disclosing Party to protect themselves from potential financial and legal risks associated with your work. So, yes, you could be held responsible for legal fees if a third party sues them due to your actions. It's important to carefully review this clause and consider its implications before signing the contract.",
